<subSubSection pageId="274" pageNumber="275" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="274" pageNumber="275">
Genus 
<taxonomicName LSID="2FC387E8-66B5-FF9D-947C-D1EEB44C46AB" authority="Fabricius, 1775" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Scarites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scarites" order="Coleoptera" pageId="274" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Scarites Fabricius, 1775</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="274" pageNumber="275" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="274" pageNumber="275">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Scarites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="274" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Scarites</taxonomicName>
Fabricius, 1775: 249. Type species: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Scarites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="274" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subterraneus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="274" pageNumber="275">Scarites subterraneus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Fabricius, 1775 designated by Andrewes (1929: 225). Etymology. From the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="274" pageNumber="275">scaritis</emphasis>
(gem of the color of the fish named 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="274" pageNumber="275">scaros</emphasis>
, probably a wrasse, in Pliny the Elder) [masculine].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="274" pageNumber="275" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="274" pageNumber="275">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="274" pageNumber="275">
About 190 species (Lorenz 2005: 137-140) arrayed in four subgenera: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dostal" authorityYear="1996" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Orientolobus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="274" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="274" pageNumber="275">Orientolobus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dostal (eight Indo-African species), 
<taxonomicName class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Parallelomorphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="274" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="274" pageNumber="275">Parallelomorphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Motschulsky (15 Old World species), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Scarites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="274" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="274" pageNumber="275">Scarites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s.str. (about 130 species), and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chaudoir" authorityYear="1855" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Taeniolobus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="274" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="274" pageNumber="275">Taeniolobus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Chaudoir (about 40 Neotropical species). The genus is more diversified in term of species in the tropics of the Old World (about 60.5% of the world fauna) than anywhere else.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="274" pageNumber="275" type="identification">
<paragraph pageId="274" pageNumber="275">Identification.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="274" pageNumber="275">
